<review>Great place for general medical treatment. I came here first time after got bit by my cat and had a pretty bad infection on my hand. The front desk personal was able to tell me if they had Tetanus shot for me before they charge me visit fee. (Thumbs up!)
The second time I was here to see my primary doctor-Dr. Johnson. She is very nice and patient even I was her last patient of that day. She did Pap smear, breast cancer check, and offered to do blood test.
They also have Chinese medicine department which does acupuncture and cupping. I was. Dry lucky to be scheduled with Dr. Hsueh. She noticed immediately that I have minor scoliosis on my lower back. She did acupuncture on my back, shoulders and knees. That was a very relaxing and healing session.< /review>< gmap_id>

< Review>
Usually a great experience. Both times with my asthma attacks, I've been treated very well. Last experience though not so much. I came in to discuss a rash that had been on my leg and was now much worse. The male doctor was impatient and rude.  He said it was shingles and that was that. He basically dismissed all my questions quickly and rushed me out of the room after just 10 minutes of my appointment, clearly his mind made up. Well I went to another clinic and found I that  I did not have the shingles but an allergic reaction of a sort that had gotten very out of hand.Obviously,  you can' t let one bad experience determine whether or not to return but I certainly hope I'll be received by a doctor more patient and understanding.<//Review>

<user_id>107274110985470023940</user_id><Name>Phil King<//Name>< Date>
1579673362462< /Date>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
We love Kobeya, our neighborhood Japanese restaurant. We've been going here for Japanese curry (with chicken cutlet) for 6-7 years, and lately have been happy that they've added ramen. I was a little worried that the ramen might not be up to San Mateo standards, but its actually great. Otherwise we love this place for bento boxes, simpler sushi rolls, and curry. This is an informal place that is comfortable for any weeknight meal. Head across the street to Kaori if you want full-on sushi or fancier (not better) Japanese food.</review>

<user>100873326786677282799</user>< user_name>
Teresa K.</user_name>
<time>1468125532605< /time><Rate>3</Rate>< Text>
Cute little place on a single street with lots of fantastic little stores/restaurants, Kobeya offers 7 versions of their "Kobeya curry", including tonkatsu curry, chicken katsu curry, gyoza curry, vegetarian, and even a curry-only option in a bowl without rice. The curry was OK; not too salty, but not very flavorful either. I had the chicken katsu, and the katsu was crisped well. They also have several options of simple sushi rolls for those not in the mood for curry, and a vegetarian menu too. However, don't expect any fancy rolls, bento boxes, udon, etc.; this place has a relatively simple menu. The prices are also low; $5-8 for most of their entrees. The eating area in the restaurant is small and bare/simple in its decor, but clean and bright. The plates and plastic cups were also very simple, akin to what is typically seen in a cafeteria. The service on a Saturday afternoon was not great -- we had to refill our own water, and napkins were not given to us (I felt this is a notable mis-step given that curry can get a little messy and stain-y).

Food: 3/5
Service: 2/5
Ambience: 4/5

Verdict: A cute place if you're looking for simple, straightforward Japanese curry that won't break the bank. Could work on service and making the curry taste a bit more memorable.< /Text>

< Review>
I've been here seemingly millions of times to watch the birds and more. I've photographed Red-Tailed Hawks, Great Egrets, Snowy Egrets (but no Snowy Owls!), even a Black Necked Stilt in recent years! I've even spotted a Long-Billed Curlew in these marshes, but PLEASE: this is a protected wildlife area: NO boats, canoes or the sorts, and no walking through the sandy areas. Stay on established paths and trails!! Also a fabulous place to catch a blazing Golden gate sunset!< /Review>

<Review>Crissy Field is part of an urban national park, which, due to its location and scenic views, is popular with both locals, tourists, and dogs.

Crissy Field reopened in 2001. New and rebuilt sidewalks, boardwalks, and trails connect the field north to Fort Point, the Warming Hut (a cafe), and south to the Crissy Field Center, an environmental education center, and the Marina District. Since that time many buildings were restored and leased out as housing, office space, retail, and recreational facilities. The old temporary wood barracks were demolished and the grass airfield restored. Letterman Army Hospital, a large concrete structure, literally was ground to dust and the concrete recycled. In its place George Lucas relocated Industrial Light & Magic.<//Review>< user>

< review>
Go here if you're strictly looking for watches and don't care about service. They have a limited collection of watches, mostly luxury brands, all on fairly good deals. The service, even on a weekday afternoon, is lethargic and meh-I-wish-I-was-sitting-home-I'm-booored. While I understand we all feel that way (often? ;) ), it's hard to dismiss that in a store where you need an associate to even check out a watch. While they don't have an extensive collection, it may not be a big deal - depending on how much scourging you typically do, before you've decided the chosen one!< /review>
